I spent 3 years living in Thailand in mid-90s and fell in love in Gai Yang (grilled chicken). Since moving to the US 20 years ago, I have been eating Gai yang in various Thai restaurants all across the US. Today, I ordered Gai Yang at SONG. This is the WORST Gai Yang I ever tasted in my life. Actually I didn't even get to eat it. Just opening the paperbag containing the chicken made me sick: the bad smell was over-powering. It smelled like rotten chicken. I suspect the chicken wasn't well conserved (cold chain) before it was cooked so it went bad. can't believe a well-respected Thai restaurant will sell such horrendous-smelling Gai Yang. Am totally disappointed.

Song is, without hyperbole, the best Thai restaurant that exists in America. Brooklyn, and NYC as a whole, have many fantastic Thai restaurants that are all great, but Song overshadows them all. I have never had anything here that wasn’t simply amazing. The spring rolls are incredible and all of their noodle meals are incredible. Plus, the prices are good for the city and you get way more food than you really should be eating in one sitting, but it’s too good to not finish.

If I could give 0 stars I would. I’ve been going to song for over 13 years since moving into the area. Service and food use to be amazing but it has only gone downhill in the past 2 years. I went in for dinner with my husband tonight, the pad Thai was extremely soggy and it seemed to have been drizzled with too much of some super sweet sauce. While the food was horrible our server for most of the night was  okay. We didn’t see him again before we left so we assumed his shift was over. My husband wasn’t comfortable leaving the tip on the table since he we wanted to make sure it went to that particular server. I told my husband let’s  leave it with the concierge before we leave. I wanted to use the  restroom before we did all of that and I put my coat on as there were still people coming in. As we approached the concierge and I left my husband to head into the restroom, a very rude and stern faced gentleman along with another young lady approached my husband and asked him why we didn’t leave a tip? Keep in mind I wasn’t dressed to head out. I heard a part of the conversation as I walked into the bathroom and I was in awe. My husband is a pretty chill guy and simply told them “please relax my wife just needs to use to rest room, we are not even dressed to leave”. Needless to say I came out of the restroom extremely pissed. We frequent many restaurants all over the world and NEVER has that ever happened to us. I went on to explain to the gentleman that it’s not okay to assume anything of your customers especially embarrass them for a tip without even asking anything.To assume something of your paying customers and make the feel embarrassed even before checking in and finding out anything is disheartening and for that WE WILL NEVER EAT AT SONG AGAIN. FOOD IS NO GOOD ANYMORE AND MANAGEMENT IS EVEN WORSE.

Extremely hit or miss, but has generally gone down in quality over time. It used to be a top-notch high quality spot but that has become less the case these days. And while I've never been sick from the many times I've eaten here, I know people who have been (and even at the same table with a different entrée).  It's a real take it or leave it kind of establishment but from the looks of it, they don't rely on reviews too much as it's always busy. When the price is right, people will come.  I'd update again on a next visit, but the last few were pretty subpar.

When you want Thai food, come here. The service is friendly and brisk, and the food is tasty. While mostly indoor seating, warmer days can allow seating in the garden. Try the handwritten specials - they are regularly the best items on the menu, but the usual suspects are always there for your indulgence.
Great  place to eat and excellent food and service.

The food at Song was ok, the restaurant was pretty empty when I went there with a group of friends so we were seated immediately. While eating I realize the waitress hardly ever came back to see how we were doing or if we needed anything. When the check comes the waitress goes on to say when tipping it has to be more than the taxes. In my mind I'm wondering "why are you dictating how much tip We should be giving you ?" So I leave a tip regardless of the lack of service and dictatorship. While we are leaving she approaches me saying it needs to be more. No where in NYC does it say I have to tip you it's not like I left $2 /$1 on the table. I found the waitress to be rude and it came off as harassment. I will never be going back to Song this was the first and last time for me.
